	<div class=3D"article ck-content"><h2 dir=3D"ltr">Pig Latin Translator&nbs=
p;</h2>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Elcomeway otay ordplaysway!</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Any idea what that says? It says Welcome to Wordplays! It=E2=
=80=99s Pig Latin, a code language with a widely debated origin.&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">If you're looking for a fun way to create secret messages an=
d communicate with friends, Pig Latin is the language for you. Although it =
looks challenging, Pig Latin isn=E2=80=99t too difficult to figure out once=
 you know the rules. The resulting translation is a humorous code that conc=
eals your message from others.&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Use the Pig Latin Translator above to decode words or senten=
ces from Pig Latin to English or translate English to Pig Latin to create y=
our own secret sentences.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2 dir=3D"ltr">The History of Pig Latin&nbsp;</h2>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Although the exact origins of the language remain a mystery,=
 dog latin or hog latin (early forms of Pig Latin) can be traced back to th=
e 1589 Shakespearean play <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love%27s=
_Labour%27s_Lost">Love's Labour's Lost</a>.&nbsp; In the mid-1800=E2=80=99s=
 we saw hog latin and pig latin resurface in several periodicals. The Pig L=
atin we know today was first seen in an early 1900=E2=80=99s song by <a hre=
f=3D"https://archive.org/details/78_pig-latin-love-i-yay-ove-lay_arthur-fie=
lds-gilbert-friedland_gbia0011253a">Authur Fields called Pig Latin Love</a>=
, a true ode to the comical language.&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">You can thank the <a href=3D"https://www.threestooges.com/">=
Three Stooges</a> for making two Pig Latin words mainstream. The Pig Latin =
version of the word =E2=80=9Cnix=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cixnay=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9Cicksnay=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cscram=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Camscray=E2=80=
=9D are regularly used in American English today. =E2=80=9CIxnay=E2=80=9D m=
eaning =E2=80=9Cnothing, or to cancel=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Camscray=E2=80=
=9D meaning to =E2=80=9Cgo away=E2=80=9D. These words first appeared in the=
 trio=E2=80=99s 1930=E2=80=99s comedy skits. Anksthay! Moe, Larry and Curle=
y.&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h2 dir=3D"ltr">Pig Latin Translator&nbsp;</h2>

<p dir=3D"ltr">To use the Pig Latin Translator, enter your word or phrase i=
nto the text box and click =E2=80=9CEnglish=E2=80=9D to translate your text=
 from Pig Latin to English. Within seconds you=E2=80=99ll have decoded the =
secret cipher. To create your own mystery message, enter your text into the=
 text box and click =E2=80=9CPig Latin=E2=80=9D.&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Want to share your message with friends? Enter the recipient=
's email into the field below the message and click =E2=80=9CEmail this mes=
sage.=E2=80=9D&nbsp; Avehay unfay!<br>
&nbsp;</p>

<h2 dir=3D"ltr">How to Speak Pig Latin?&nbsp;</h2>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Follow the steps below to learn how to read, write and speak=
 in Pig Latin.&nbsp;</p>

<ol>
	<li dir=3D"ltr">
	<p dir=3D"ltr">For words that begin with a consonant followed by a vowel, =
take the first letter of the word before the vowel, add it to the end of th=
e word and add an =E2=80=9Cay=E2=80=9D.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ol>

<p dir=3D"ltr">For example: Boggle =3D oggle + b + ay =3D ogglebay<br>
&nbsp;</p>

<ol start=3D"2">
	<li dir=3D"ltr">
	<p dir=3D"ltr">For words that begin with two consonants followed by a vowe=
l, move both consonants to the end of the word and add an =E2=80=9Cay=E2=80=
=9D.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ol>

<p>For example: Crossword =3D ossword + cr + ay =3D osswordcray</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">What about words with multiple syllables, like the example =
=E2=80=9CCrossword=E2=80=9D above? Some versions of Pig Latin split up the =
syllables. If you want to create multi-syllable words in Pig Latin, add =E2=
=80=9Cay=E2=80=9D after each syllable with a consonant.</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">For example: Crossword =3D oss + cr + ay &amp; ord + w + ay =
=3D osscray ordway&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">&nbsp;</p>

<ol start=3D"3">
	<li dir=3D"ltr">
	<p dir=3D"ltr">For words that start with a vowel, add =E2=80=9Chay=E2=80=
=9D, =E2=80=9Cway=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cyay=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cay=E2=80=9D t=
o the end of the word.&nbsp;</p>
	</li>
</ol>

<p dir=3D"ltr">For example: October =3D october + yay =3D octoberyay</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">&nbsp;</p>

<p dir=3D"ltr">Now that you know the rules, give it a shot! All you need is=
 someone to speak with and with the help of the Pig Latin Translator you=E2=
=80=99ll be fluent in no time.&nbsp;</p>

<p><br>
&nbsp;</p>
